A `friend` class in C++ is a class that is allowed to access private and protected members of another class. When a class is declared as a `friend` of another class, it can access the latter's private and protected members as if it were a member of that class. This mechanism is used to allow a particular class to access the internal details of another class for the purpose of enhancing collaboration between classes without breaking encapsulation completely.

Here's a basic example:

```cpp
class Box {
    double width;
public:
    double getWidth() const { return width; }
    void setWidth(double wid) { width = wid; }
    friend class BoxManager; // BoxManager can access private members of Box
};

class BoxManager {
public:
    void printWidth(const Box& b) {
        // Access private member of Box
        std::cout << "Width of box: " << b.width << std::endl;
    }
};
```

In this example, `BoxManager` is a friend of `Box`, so it can access the private member `width` directly.

