1. **Virtual [`putc`](command:_github.copilot.openSymbolFromReferences?%5B%7B%22%24mid%22%3A1%2C%22path%22%3A%22%2Ff%3A%2FProject%2FDelta%2Fembedded%2Fclc_test_firmware%2Ffirmwareutil%2Fhal%2Fsrc%2FSTM32Fx%2FUARTDriver.cpp%22%2C%22scheme%22%3A%22file%22%7D%2C%7B%22line%22%3A50%2C%22character%22%3A17%7D%5D "firmwareutil/hal/src/STM32Fx/UARTDriver.cpp") Function:**
   ```cpp
   virtual void putc(uint8_t c) const = 0;
   ```
   This is a pure virtual function that takes a [`uint8_t`](command:_github.copilot.openSymbolFromReferences?%5B%7B%22%24mid%22%3A1%2C%22path%22%3A%22%2Fc%3A%2FProgram%20Files%20(x86)%2FGNU%20Arm%20Embedded%20Toolchain%2F10%202021.10%2Farm-none-eabi%2Finclude%2Fsys%2F_stdint.h%22%2C%22scheme%22%3A%22file%22%7D%2C%7B%22line%22%3A23%2C%22character%22%3A18%7D%5D "c:/Program Files (x86)/GNU Arm Embedded Toolchain/10 2021.10/arm-none-eabi/include/sys/_stdint.h") (unsigned 8-bit integer) as an argument. Being a pure virtual function, it means that any derived class must provide an implementation for this function. This function is intended to transmit an unsigned character.

2. **Non-Virtual [`putc`](command:_github.copilot.openSymbolFromReferences?%5B%7B%22%24mid%22%3A1%2C%22path%22%3A%22%2Ff%3A%2FProject%2FDelta%2Fembedded%2Fclc_test_firmware%2Ffirmwareutil%2Fhal%2Fsrc%2FSTM32Fx%2FUARTDriver.cpp%22%2C%22scheme%22%3A%22file%22%7D%2C%7B%22line%22%3A50%2C%22character%22%3A17%7D%5D "firmwareutil/hal/src/STM32Fx/UARTDriver.cpp") Function:**
   ```cpp
   void putc(char c) const;
   ```
   This is a regular member function that takes a `char` (signed 8-bit integer) as an argument. This function is not pure virtual and can have an implementation within the `UARTDriver` class itself. This function is intended to transmit a signed character.

### Why Two [`putc`](command:_github.copilot.openSymbolFromReferences?%5B%7B%22%24mid%22%3A1%2C%22path%22%3A%22%2Ff%3A%2FProject%2FDelta%2Fembedded%2Fclc_test_firmware%2Ffirmwareutil%2Fhal%2Fsrc%2FSTM32Fx%2FUARTDriver.cpp%22%2C%22scheme%22%3A%22file%22%7D%2C%7B%22line%22%3A50%2C%22character%22%3A17%7D%5D "firmwareutil/hal/src/STM32Fx/UARTDriver.cpp") Functions?

The presence of two [`putc`](command:_github.copilot.openSymbolFromReferences?%5B%7B%22%24mid%22%3A1%2C%22path%22%3A%22%2Ff%3A%2FProject%2FDelta%2Fembedded%2Fclc_test_firmware%2Ffirmwareutil%2Fhal%2Fsrc%2FSTM32Fx%2FUARTDriver.cpp%22%2C%22scheme%22%3A%22file%22%7D%2C%7B%22line%22%3A50%2C%22character%22%3A17%7D%5D "firmwareutil/hal/src/STM32Fx/UARTDriver.cpp") functions with different signatures allows the class to handle both signed and unsigned characters. The virtual function ensures that derived classes must implement the method for transmitting unsigned characters, while the non-virtual function can provide a default implementation for transmitting signed characters.

### Example Implementation

Here is a possible implementation scenario:

```cpp
class MyUARTDriver : public UARTDriver {
public:
    void putc(uint8_t c) const override {
        // Implementation for transmitting an unsigned character
    }

    void putc(char c) const override {
        // Implementation for transmitting a signed character
    }
};
```

In this example, `MyUARTDriver` provides its own implementation for both `putc` functions. The virtual `putc` function must be overridden because it is pure virtual, while the non-virtual `putc` function can be optionally overridden if a different behavior is desired.

### Summary

The syntax allows the `UARTDriver` class to define a contract for transmitting unsigned characters via the pure virtual function, while also providing a mechanism to handle signed characters through a regular member function. This design provides flexibility and enforces certain behaviors in derived classes.

